[[table]]
[[row]]
[[hcell]]
INCIDENT REPORT AAFD-I-2028-37
[[/hcell]]
[[/row]]
[[row]]
[[cell]]
**DATE:** 2028/09/08

**FOREWORD:** Minor hazardous materials breach. See attached interview transcript.

**RECORDING OFFICER:** Dr. Nhung Ngo (Chair, Psychology and Parapsychology, Site-43)
[[/cell]]
[[/row]]
[[row]]
[[hcell]]
¬´ BEGIN TRANSCRIPT ¬ª
[[/hcell]]
[[/row]]
[[row]]
[[hcell]]

[[div class="blockquote"]]

= //<Dr. Dougall Deering, Chief of Acroamatic Abatement at Site-43, is sitting across from Dr. Ngo at her desk. His hands are bandaged. He is very still, as he is recovering from heavy sedation. There is a small red plastic box on the desk beside Dr. Ngo's recording device, decorated with the heraldry of a confectionery company. He is staring at it.>//

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] We'll ease you into this.

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Okay.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] What were you doing in Acroamatic Abatement Facility AAF-D on September the 8th, 2028?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Supervising a flush.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] And what does that entail?

= //<Dr. Deering's voice is flat and without affect, as though he is reciting from memory.>//

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] AAF-D is the powerhouse of 43's abatement plant. It's the single largest Anomalous waste facility ever constructed. Since the effluence crisis escalated globally, it's been doing non-stop quadruple-duty. Every few years we have to shut it down, for a period not exceeding one hour -- anything longer and the whole system backs up irrecoverably -- and pump the overflow into the anachronic sump below the Site.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] Why?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Because output is severely lagging behind input. We're overwhelmed, and we're operating on triage principles. Any substance requiring too much time or too heavy a resource commitment to abate has to be set aside as impractical, because certain other abatements are too time-sensitive to delay. Some of the Anomalous effects of the waste we process can worsen the longer they're kept in the pipeline, and that's not even getting into what it does to the pipes themselves. When we perform the flush, they're often already white-hot, or ice cold, or humming obscenities in Latin. It's always a close call, because we can't afford to do it more regularly. Not on our schedule.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] So this flush resets the equipment to factory?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Not hardly. It just buys us a little more time. The next flush...

= //<Dr. Deering sighs. His tone is becoming strident.>//

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Probably not even a year.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] But you can still pump what you can't abate into the sump, right.

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] For now. Not for much longer. It's getting full.

= //<Silence on recording.>//

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] You can cut to the chase now. I don't... I don't feel anything anyway.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] You're on a lot of painkillers. That's normal.

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Sure.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] Who was in charge of the flush this year?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Deputy Chief of Janitorial and Maintenance Ph-- Philip Eugene Deering.

[[include component:image-block
name=PhilStock.jpg
|caption=Deputy Chief Deering.
|width=175px
|align=right]]

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] Your brother.

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] My... yes.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] And you were supervising him?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Yes. No. I was... visiting him.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] Visiting him? You work at the same facility.

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Yes. We've been here together for decades, but we haven't been here //together// at all. I never speak to him. I don't want to get into that, we just... we aren't close.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] What did the two of you talk about?

= //<Dr. Deering nods at the box on the table.>//

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] That. I found it in an old box in our parents' house, cleaning out the basement. I thought he'd like to have it. I bought it for him from the general store when we were children.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] May I?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Go on.

= //<Dr. Ngo picks up the toy. It consists of a single sliding compartment. She slides it out, then back in, then back out again. She shrugs.>//

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] What does it do?

= //<Dr. Deering smiles faintly.>//

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] It makes things disappear.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] What?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Put something in it. Your pin, maybe.

= //<Dr. Ngo unclips her Site-43 badge pin and places it inside the compartment. She closes it. She opens it again. The pin is missing. She closes and opens the compartment several more times. The pin is still missing.>//

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] How does it work?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] It's magic. I'm an occultist, you know.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] Did you end up giving it to him?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] No.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] What happened instead? Take your time.

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] I'm not as familiar with the layout of F-D as I used to be. They've had to make a lot of changes to keep up with the pressure. There was a valve...

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] On the junction between the...

= //<Dr. Ngo checks her notes.>//

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] ...orphic and ambichronological outflow pipes. What does that mean?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Two very different types of esoteric effluence in side-by-side conduits. There's a junction connecting them with a series of impregnable stoppers operated by remote control, for combining their contents under specific emergency circumstances. Intermixing in rigorously-controlled amounts to neutralize both in the case of an overflow. The valve is only there to allow manual access during accidents, since it's impossible to do this with the appropriate level of care by hand. It shouldn't have moved just because I bumped into it.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] So why did it? Metal fatigue?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Maybe. Every individual facility is suffering from budget crunch, and the equipment is aging rapidly. But no... no, I think we were actually in the early stages of a total collapse already, and this was just the first sign. Those pipes were full to bursting, when they should have been almost empty...

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] Are you suggesting they hadn't been flushed properly?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] No. I don't... I can't see how. Look, they're under a lot of pressure, the people who work in AcroAbate. And the materials are unpredictable. There could have been some sort of duplicative reaction. The point is, there was a lot more effluence in the system than expected, and a lot of it's still in there now. It might have come blasting out anyway, even if I hadn't hit the valve. 

= //<Dr. Deering sighs.>//

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] But I did, so it happened the way it did. But it didn't make a difference, it definitely didn't really make a difference.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] What happened next?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] The materials mixed inappropriately, and the orphic outflow instantly became every version of itself it had ever been: before, during, and after abatement, simultaneously. It looked like an army of technicolour ghosts all melted together, bursting out of the pipes like steam.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] And then?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] And then Phil... Deputy Chief Deering, headed for the suction pump controls near the break. Every room and corridor in the entire facility has these controls; all he had to do was turn a single handle and all the emergent phenomena would get sucked into the sinkhole without further incident.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] But that's not what happened.

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] No. Instead, he was met halfway by some... //thing,// which manifested behind him, between us, away from the ghostflow. Something writhing, ethereal. It sucked up most of the airborne effluence, then crunched itself down to his size... I could //hear// the crunching, and then--

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] You don't have to r--

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] //<shouting>// And then it moved right through him, overlaid itself on him, coiled around him and started to shrink. And his eyes rolled back, his skin shrivelled in against his bones and split where his organs were, and they burst out of him, and he melted into a pile of... all over the floor... and it was gone, and he was...

= //<Dr. Deering heaves ineffectually, hyperventilating for several seconds before recovering.>//

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] I don't think he felt it.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] And then you turned the handle yourself.

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] I don't remember.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] It was captured on camera.

= //<Dr. Ngo gestures at Dr. Deering's hands.>//

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] It's how that happened. The controls were compromised. The ghosts were out too long.

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] I don't remember.

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] You've been traumatized, of course--

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] If you got it all on camera, why drag me through this again?

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] I needed to hear your version for the report.

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] My...? My //version//? What the fuck does that mean?

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] It's just standard procedure, doctor.

= //<Silence on recording.>//

[[span class="ngo"]]Dr. Ngo:[[/span]] How do I get my pin back?

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Shake it to the left. Hard.

= //<Dr. Ngo shakes the box, then opens the compartment. She retrieves her button, and reaffixes it to her jacket.>//

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] It was never gone. A slide to the right, and a little mirror to hide the evidence. No magic at all.

= //<Dr. Deering shakes his head.>//

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Just a trick.
[[/div]]

[[/hcell]]
[[/row]]
[[row]]
[[hcell]]
¬´ END TRANSCRIPT ¬ª
[[/hcell]]
[[/row]]
[[row]]
[[cell]]
**AFTERWORD:** This interview reaffirmed Dr. Deering's testimony in the immediate aftermath of the accident, in which he reported the presence of a rogue entity unrelated to the overflowing materials and responsible for his brother's death. No personnel reviewing the security camera footage of the incident are able to perceive said entity, even under mnestic treatment.

On the recommendation of Dr. Ngo and Chief Torosyan-Deering of Janitorial and Maintenance, Dr. Deering has been prescribed one year's mandatory mental health leave.
[[/cell]]
[[/row]]
